@brettbarker8444 Absolutely. You tell stories of David's 30 mighty men and all the drama that's intertwined with David's life as King....there is PLENTY to make a very legitimate 1 or 2 season show about.

I remember I first started thinking about this when I read 2 Sam 2 about how David's faced Abner's men and they chose 12 men from each side who literally walked up to their opponent, they grabbed each other by the head and thrust their swords into each other and died together. THAT IS FREAKING INSANE AND EPIC.

There is plenty of amazing war stories to be told from David's life that would be awesome on a big screen.

@benjamintodd5637 No, I'm saying that nobody taught what you exposited among anybody who called themselves "Christian" until a few centuries ago at most. You being able to allow yourself to create a overly broad and invariably incomplete representation of world events, that ignores eras of deep distress all over the world well before this time you now observe then fit that to said doctrine, does not mean that your specific doctrine appeared prior to said few centuries ago.

*_Doctrines are a subset of beliefs foundational to a person's salvation..._* No, "doctrine" is synonymous with teaching. I don't even think this distinction is more than 10 years old-- I don't remember it when I was growing up. Rather, people would use the term "doctrine" plainly derisively as a symbol of rigidity that opposed the fullness of the Christian faith as a "relationship" rather than "merely religion".

*_The Bible laid this Belief out..._* Rather, the way you read the Scriptures-- a means inherited by prior generations of a specific faith community-- informs you to read them in that manner. The rhyming of history does not mean that the _specific thing you're expositing at this moment_ is older than a few centuries.

@GreyhawkTheAngry very. the book where David kills Goliath is 1 Samuel chapter 17, but if you want specifically David's retort to Goliath:

verses 45-46: Then said David to the Philistine, Thou comest to me with a sword, and with a spear, and with a shield: but I come to thee in the name of the Lord of hosts, the God of the armies of Israel, whom thou hast defied.

      This day will the Lord deliver thee into mine hand; and I will smite thee, and take thine head from thee; and I will give the carcases of the host of the Philistines this day unto the fowls of the air, and to the wild beasts of the earth; that all the earth may know that there is a God in Israel.

@brando3342hold on, we’re this only story of faith over brawn then when Saul offered David his armor and sword then David would have taken it saying that he could use whatever and still win because faith in God is a replacement for discipline. 

But instead he says that he isn’t used to that armor and weapons and he arms himself in the manner he is expected with. Were it just a story about faith he wouldn’t have brought the stones and the sling. 

Yes the primary lesson is about faith, but it is also about diligence, cleverness and sticking to what you know works.

@ChaoticYak1 The movie ends with David becoming king of Israel. I agree that they spent considerably less time developing David's friendship with Jonathan, but to be clear they definitely did not remove it. They showed repeatedly how they were aligned in their faith and devotion to God and to one another, actually. Some of my kids cried when Jonathan died, so there was certainly enough there for people to latch onto and have some understanding of the depth of their friendship.

In other news: Man, I want to be a friend like Jonathan!

Be blessed, internet stranger!
